They want to
take her early.

18
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:21,718
Tetrahedron.

19
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:24,558
Dodecahedron.

20
00:01:24,720 --> 00:01:26,416
They're offering
a full scholarship.

21
00:01:26,440 --> 00:01:27,919
All you have to do
is get there.

22
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:30,829
Ms. Coleman...

23
00:01:31,560 --> 00:01:34,711
why don't you solve
the equation on the board?

24
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:43,192
We took up a collection

25
00:01:43,280 --> 00:01:44,679
amongst the teachers and such.

26
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:45,840
It's not a lot...

27
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:48,115
but it's enough
to help get you settled in.

28
00:01:49,120 --> 00:01:51,509
That's more than kind,
Ms. Sumner.

29
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:04,776
If the product of two terms

30
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:06,870
is zero then common sense says

31
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:10,117
at least one of the two terms
has to be zero to start with.

32
00:02:10,280 --> 00:02:13,192
So if you move all the
terms over to one side,

33
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:15,391
you can put the quadratics
into a form

34
00:02:15,480 --> 00:02:16,708
that can be factored...

35
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:18,472
allowing that side
of the equation

36
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:19,560
to equal zero.

37
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:21,856
Once you've done that,
it's pretty straightforward

38
00:02:21,880 --> 00:02:22,880
from there.

39
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:27,920
In all my years
of teaching...

40
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:31,393
I've never seen a mind like
the one your daughter has.

41
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:33,400
Katherine!

42
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:35,232
Hurry on now, love.

43
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,279
You have to go.

44
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:39,752
Let Mama tuck you in.

45
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:48,594
You have to see
what she becomes.

46
00:03:14,760 --> 00:03:16,318
Okay,
try to turn it over now.

47
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:18,949
Katherine?

48
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:20,794
Mary!

49
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:22,280
Somebody!

50
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:23,400
Katherine!

51
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:25,954
Quit staring off into space
and turn the damn car over.

52
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:27,269
I got it.

53
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:30,149
I'm not deaf.

54
00:03:30,320 --> 00:03:31,320
I wonder sometimes.

55
00:03:32,880 --> 00:03:33,880
Here it goes.

56
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:38,790
Yeah,
it's the starter.

57
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:41,793
That is definitely the starter.

58
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:43,791
This starter is starting
to make us late.

59
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:45,400
We are all gonna
end up unemployed...

60
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:47,869
riding around in this pile
of junk to work every day.

61
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:49,798
You're welcome
to walk the 16 miles.

62
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:51,991
Or sit in the back of the bus.

63
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:54,792
I won't do neither.

64
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:56,674
I'll hitchhike.

65
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:02,353
Girls.

66
00:04:08,240 --> 00:04:09,593
No crime in a
broken-down car.

67
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:11,998
No crime being Negro neither.

68
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:13,309
Button it up, Mary.

69
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,389
Nobody wants to go to
jail behind your mouth.

70
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:18,080
I'll do my best, sugar.

71
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:33,229
Not a great place for three of
y'all be having car trouble.

72
00:04:33,880 --> 00:04:36,440
We didn't pick the place,
Officer. It picked us.

73
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:38,113
You being disrespectful?

74
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:39,679
No, sir.

75
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:41,428
You have
identification on you?

76
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:43,079
Yes, sir.
Yes, sir.

77
00:04:45,080 --> 00:04:47,116
We're just on our way
to work...

78
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:48,349
at Langley.

79
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:50,879
NASA, sir.

80
00:04:51,040 --> 00:04:52,553
We do a great deal
of the calculating.

81
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:54,392
Getting our rockets
into space.

82
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:56,079
All three of you?
Yes, sir.

83
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:57,240
Yes, Officer.

84
00:04:58,720 --> 00:04:59,720
NASA.

85
00:04:59,880 --> 00:05:01,074
Now that's something.

86
00:05:02,040 --> 00:05:04,474
I had no idea
they hired...

87
00:05:04,640 --> 00:05:08,235
There are quite a few women
working in the space program.

88
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:18,911
Damn Russians are
watching us right now.

89
00:05:19,640 --> 00:05:20,914
Sputniks.

90
00:05:22,280 --> 00:05:24,077
You girls ever
meet those astronauts?

91
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,639
Mercury Seven?

92
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:27,239
Absolutely.

93
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:31,798
Uh, yes, sir. We work with
those gentlemen all the time.

94
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:34,150
Those boys are the best
we got. I'm sure of that.

95
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:35,355
Yeah.
Yeah.

96
00:05:35,480 --> 00:05:37,216
We gotta get a man up there
before the commies do.

97
00:05:37,240 --> 00:05:38,240
Yes.
Absolutely.

98
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:39,776
Whole damn country's
counting on them.

99
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:40,915
That's for certain.

100
00:05:41,080 --> 00:05:42,638
Hard being of service
broken down

101
00:05:42,760 --> 00:05:44,478
on the side
of the road, though.

102
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:46,352
Right, right.

103
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:48,192
Well, do y'all need a tow
or something?

104
00:05:48,360 --> 00:05:49,960
No, thank you, Officer.
I think I got it.

105
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:51,189
Just give me my...

106
00:05:51,360 --> 00:05:54,636
Just need to bypass
the starter.

107
00:05:57,040 --> 00:05:58,996
She's good at this stuff.

108
00:05:59,600 --> 00:06:01,750
Whoo! Attagirl.

109
00:06:02,880 --> 00:06:03,880
We're all set.

110
00:06:04,040 --> 00:06:06,429
Well, hell, least I can do
is give y'all an escort.

111
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:08,158
I imagine you're
running late to work.

112
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:09,992
No, sir. We wouldn't
wanna bother you.

113
00:06:10,160 --> 00:06:11,440
That would be
wonderful, Officer.

114
00:06:12,720 --> 00:06:13,994
Thank you so much, sir.

115
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:15,080
Follow me.

116
00:06:15,160 --> 00:06:16,160
I'm driving.

117
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:18,016
Hurry up, Dorothy,
before he changes his mind.

118
00:06:18,040 --> 00:06:20,190
- We're coming.
- Hold your horses.

119
00:06:26,880 --> 00:06:28,096
Yes!
Whoa, slow down, Mary!

120
00:06:28,120 --> 00:06:29,599
Mary, slow down!
You're too close!

121
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:30,816
Be quiet.
He said to follow him.

122
00:06:30,840 --> 00:06:32,034
He didn't mean
up his behind!

123
00:06:35,320 --> 00:06:37,311
Dear Lord, I don't even
know where to begin!

124
00:06:37,480 --> 00:06:38,833
Oh, I'll tell you
where to begin.

125
00:06:39,040 --> 00:06:41,634
Three Negro women are chasing
a white police officer

126
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:43,552
down the highway
in Hampton, Virginia...

127
00:06:43,720 --> 00:06:45,551
1961.

128
00:06:45,720 --> 00:06:49,554
Ladies, that there
is a God-ordained miracle.

129
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:53,672
And, tomorrow,
I'm riding the bus.

130
00:06:58,040 --> 00:06:59,758
I'm moving over

131
00:07:04,200 --> 00:07:06,509
I'm on a sidewalk

132
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:08,431
I'm going over

133
00:07:15,400 --> 00:07:17,914
Lift off
is good. Trajectory is stable.

134
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:20,195
Show me.

135
00:07:21,240 --> 00:07:22,514
No, exactly.

136
00:07:22,680 --> 00:07:24,955
40.349110 degrees North.

137
00:07:29,920 --> 00:07:32,354
Ascent angle 46. 56.

138
00:07:32,880 --> 00:07:35,519
Approaching
7,400 miles per hour.

139
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:38,553
118 seconds.

140
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:43,072
Boosters have disengaged.

141
00:07:48,200 --> 00:07:49,599
Second stage success.

142
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,400
Korabl-Sputnik 4 is orbital.

143
00:07:56,280 --> 00:07:58,430
Orbital entry is established.

144
00:07:58,600 --> 00:08:00,192
Russian orbital entry
is established.

145
00:08:02,600 --> 00:08:03,794
Jim Webb.

146
00:08:05,080 --> 00:08:06,559
Yes, Mr. President.

147
00:08:07,240 --> 00:08:08,912
We certainly are, sir.

148
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:11,912
Uh, it looks like
they've achieved

149
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:13,353
at least one orbit, maybe two.

150
00:08:15,560 --> 00:08:18,154
Chernushka is ready
to go again.

151
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:22,791
So is our comrade, Ivan,
a brave space traveler.

152
00:08:22,960 --> 00:08:25,599
We have proven life can
be sustained in space.

153
00:08:25,760 --> 00:08:27,830
Now we will be first
to send a human.

154
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,992
A damn dog
and a damn mannequin.

155
00:08:33,440 --> 00:08:38,275
And then, a 1.6 megaton RDS-37
thermonuclear warhead...

156
00:08:38,920 --> 00:08:41,150
drops down in the middle
of Des Moines.

157
00:08:41,320 --> 00:08:42,720
Well, that's
a pretty big jump, sir.

158
00:08:42,800 --> 00:08:43,800
What?

159
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:46,110
Just that...
Who the hell is he?

160
00:08:46,280 --> 00:08:48,316
Paul Stafford,
our lead engineer, Mr. Webb.

161
00:08:48,480 --> 00:08:49,680
I think what
he meant to say...

162
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:52,240
is that speculation, at least
on our side of the equation...

163
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:54,311
by definition can be...

164
00:08:54,480 --> 00:08:56,118
just a little dangerous.

165
00:08:56,280 --> 00:08:57,315
Dangerous?

166
00:08:57,480 --> 00:08:59,948
You know what's dangerous,
Mr. Stafford?

167
00:09:00,120 --> 00:09:02,156
Inaction and indecision.

168
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:04,950
The Russians
have a spy satellite

169
00:09:05,040 --> 00:09:06,040
lapping the planet,

170
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:08,270
taking pictures
of God knows what!

171
00:09:09,480 --> 00:09:11,789
The President is demanding
an immediate response.

172
00:09:11,960 --> 00:09:13,520
No more delay.
Alan Shepard, John Glenn,

173
00:09:13,640 --> 00:09:14,776
your uncle Bob,
it doesn't matter.

174
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:15,869
Get us up there, Harrison.

175
00:09:16,040 --> 00:09:18,235
We can't justify
a space program

176
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:20,675
that doesn't put
anything in space.

177
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:24,471
How'd that feel
in there, Paul?

178
00:09:24,640 --> 00:09:26,631
You think you enlightened
the administrator?

179
00:09:27,560 --> 00:09:28,560
Hmm?

180
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:30,870
No, he didn't look
enlightened to me.

181
00:09:31,320 --> 00:09:32,992
He look enlightened to you, Sam?

182
00:09:33,160 --> 00:09:34,229
Not particularly.

183
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:35,469
And just so you know,

184
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:37,136
he's not wrong about
what he said in there.

185
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:38,559
You know that, right?

186
00:09:38,760 --> 00:09:40,432
Because now that
they can get up there,

187
00:09:40,520 --> 00:09:41,669
a bomb will follow.

188
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:44,675
It's what happens
to all our good ideas.

189
00:09:45,160 --> 00:09:47,071
I imagine theirs too.
Where's...

190
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:48,714
Where's the machine?

191
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:49,880
Any day now,
Mr. Harrison.

192
00:09:50,360 --> 00:09:52,157
Any day now.
Yes, sir.

193
00:09:52,360 --> 00:09:54,669
What's it called?
The initials.

194
00:09:54,840 --> 00:09:56,034
The IBM.

195
00:09:56,240 --> 00:09:57,719
International Business Machines.

196
00:09:57,880 --> 00:10:00,553
Space is a business.

197
00:10:00,760 --> 00:10:02,557
I need a mathematician.

198
00:10:02,720 --> 00:10:04,000
I'll put in
another request, sir.

199
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:05,280
"Another request."
Jesus Christ.

200
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:07,556
We don't have a single person
in this entire building

201
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:10,029
that can handle
analytic geometry?

202
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:11,240
That's what
I've been told.

203
00:10:11,360 --> 00:10:12,496
Tell me something else, Ruth...

204
00:10:12,520 --> 00:10:13,953
like we're gonna find
such a person

205
00:10:14,120 --> 00:10:15,519
before the Russians
plant a flag

206
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:16,600
on the damn moon.

207
00:10:26,760 --> 00:10:27,760
A real good time.

208
00:10:27,920 --> 00:10:29,000
All right, Gloria.

209
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:30,680
You'll be with engineering,
building four.

210
00:10:32,760 --> 00:10:33,875
Ladies, ladies.

211
00:10:34,040 --> 00:10:35,576
If you're tardy,
you don't get an assignment.

212
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:36,696
If you don't get
an assignment,

213
00:10:36,720 --> 00:10:37,789
you don't have a job.

214
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:40,149
Eleanor.

215
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:41,912
Data Reduction, building 202.

216
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:43,235
Data Reduction?

217
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:44,958
You're welcome
to join the charmers

218
00:10:45,080 --> 00:10:46,593
in Magnetoplasma Dynamics.

219
00:10:46,760 --> 00:10:47,909
Oh, no, ma'am.

220
00:10:48,120 --> 00:10:50,475
Thank you.
Data Reduction is just fine.

221
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:52,153
Mm-hmm.

222
00:10:53,240 --> 00:10:54,559
Mary.
Present.

223
00:10:54,720 --> 00:10:57,154
The Mercury Seven prototype
has arrived for testing.

224
00:10:57,320 --> 00:10:59,276
Mr. Zielinski's
requesting you

225
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:01,275
for permanent assignment.

226
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:02,759
Are you serious?

227
00:11:02,920 --> 00:11:03,920
Get moving.

228
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,116
Ooh, thank you, Jesus.

229
00:11:08,280 --> 00:11:09,395
Thank you, Jesus!

230
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:11,995
Oh, thank you. Mary, Mary.
Keep it inside.

231
00:11:12,920 --> 00:11:14,512
Okay. I'm sorry, Dor.

232
00:11:16,920 --> 00:11:18,273
All right, Ms. Late.

233
00:11:18,440 --> 00:11:20,476
You will also be supporting
the east group.

234
00:11:21,840 --> 00:11:23,319
Mrs. Mitchell.

235
00:11:23,480 --> 00:11:25,436
We're on double-time
this morning, girls.

236
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:27,909
I need these calculations
before lunch.

237
00:11:28,600 --> 00:11:31,353
Space Task Group
needs a computer, ASAP.

238
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:34,109
Someone with a handle
on analytic geometry.

239
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:37,110
We can't fill that position
out of the east group.

240
00:11:37,280 --> 00:11:38,429
Permanent or temp?

241
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:40,955
Everything's temporary, Dorothy.

242
00:11:41,120 --> 00:11:42,155
You have someone?

243
00:11:42,320 --> 00:11:43,514
Yes, ma'am.

244
00:11:43,720 --> 00:11:45,631
Katherine's
the gal for that.

245
00:11:45,800 --> 00:11:47,950
She can handle any numbers
you put in front of her.

246
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:49,439
I'll check her credentials.

247
00:11:51,800 --> 00:11:53,950
Didn't think I'd come
all the way down here.

248
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:55,838
Here. Finish passing
those out.

249
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,000
Yes, ma'am.

250
00:12:02,040 --> 00:12:03,598
Mrs. Mitchell.

251
00:12:03,760 --> 00:12:04,760
If I could...

252
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:08,709
My application
for supervisor, ma'am.

253
00:12:08,880 --> 00:12:10,656
Was just wondering if they're
still considering me

254
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:12,033
for that position.

255
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:13,269
Yes.

256
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:15,510
Well, the official
word is no.

257
00:12:16,120 --> 00:12:18,760
They're not assigning a permanent
supervisor for the colored group.

258
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:20,879
May I ask why?

259
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:22,519
I don't know why.

260
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,199
I didn't ask why.

261
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:25,918
We need a supervisor, ma'am.

262
00:12:26,080 --> 00:12:28,071
We haven't had one
since Miss Jansen got sick.

263
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:29,593
It's been almost a year.

264
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:31,352
Things are working
just fine as is.

265
00:12:31,560 --> 00:12:34,313
I'm doing the work
of a supervisor.

266
00:12:34,640 --> 00:12:36,835
Well, that's NASA for you.

267
00:12:37,600 --> 00:12:40,319
Fast with rocket ships,
slow with advancement.

268
00:12:40,920 --> 00:12:43,150
Get those trajectory
calcs worked out.

269
00:12:43,360 --> 00:12:44,952
We need them
for the Redstone test.

